<li class="comment byuser comment-author-mcrustawildernesscat-com bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-89172">
<article id="comment-89172" class="comment">
<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
<img alt='small mallory photo' src='https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/cropped-Small-pfp-44x44.jpg' srcset='https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/cropped-Small-pfp-88x88.jpg 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' loading='lazy' decoding='async' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='https://www.wildernesscat.com/' rel='external nofollow ugc' class='url'>Mallory Crusta</a></b> <span>Post author</span></cite><a href="https://allaboutcats.com/best-cat-water-fountain#comment-89172"><time datetime="2022-09-20T17:55:43+00:00">Sep 20, 2022 at 5:55 pm</time></a> </header>
<section class="comment-content comment">
<p>This is an interesting detail to consider. All of them build the filters into either the pump housing or some other part of the fountain, not in a disposable plastic housing. The closest is the Petkit, which does place the prefilter in an extra plastic housing, but you don&#8217;t need to buy replacements and can use the same one for the life of the fountain.</p>
</section>
